Exercise 1

  1. The relationship will be positive: as % first gen increases, % Pell elligible will also tend to increase.
#part b
ggplot(scorecard, aes(x = firstgen_pct, y = pell_pct)) +
  geom_point()
Warning: Removed 145 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
(`geom_point()`).

  1. There is a moderately strong, positive, linear relationship. There is one potential outlier with over 80% first gen students.

  2. Yes

Exercise 2

#part a
scorecard %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(pell_pct, firstgen_pct, 
                              use = "complete.obs"))
# A tibble: 1 Ã 1
  correlation
        <dbl>
1       0.627
  1. The correlation of 0.627 indicates a moderately strong positive linear relationship.

Exercise 3

#part a
model1 <- lm(pell_pct ~ firstgen_pct, scorecard)
tidy(model1)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 5
  term         estimate std.error statistic   p.value
  <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 (Intercept)     6.92     1.02        6.79 1.61e- 11
2 firstgen_pct    0.967    0.0304     31.9  3.78e-172

  1. \(\hat{y} = 6.923 + 0.967x\)

  2. For an institution with 0% first generation students, we would expect the 6.92% of its students to be Pell elligible, on average.

  3. For every one percentage point increase in first generation, % Pell elligible increases by 0.967 percentage points on average.

Exercise 4

#part a code
glance(model1)[1]
# A tibble: 1 Ã 1
  r.squared
      <dbl>
1     0.393
  1. 39.3% of the variability in % Pell elligible can be explained by % First gen.

Exercise 6

#part a code
model1_aug <- augment(model1)
ggplot(data = model1_aug, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x = "Fitted values",
       y = "Residuals")
  1. Yes, a linear model is appropriate because there is no apparent pattern in the residual plot. The residuals are randomly scattered around 0.

Exercise 9

(1pt: graded on completion) Our analysis suggests that as average SAT score of a university goes up, % of Pell eligible students tends to go down. The article notes that rich students tend to do better on standardized tests such as the SAT for reasons unrelated to ability and potential. Therefore, low-income students may be disproportionately excluded from âeliteâ schools with competitive admissions processes. A university concerned with equity and inclusion should ensure that its admissions criteria do not unfairly screen out low-income students.
